{"parse":{"title":"Q-principle","pageid":54602226,"revid":800437014,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>In the <a href=\"/wiki/Neo-Gricean\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Neo-Gricean\">Neo-Gricean</a> approach to <a href=\"/wiki/Semantics\" title=\"Semantics\">semantics</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Pragmatics\" title=\"Pragmatics\">pragmatics</a> championed by <a href=\"/wiki/Yale\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Yale\">Yale</a> linguist <a href=\"/wiki/Laurence_Horn\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Laurence Horn\">Laurence Horn</a>, the Q-Principle (\"Q\" for \"Quantity\") is a reformulation of <a href=\"/wiki/Paul_Grice\" title=\"Paul Grice\">Paul Grice</a>'s maxim of Quantity (<i>see</i> <a href=\"/wiki/Gricean_maxims\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Gricean maxims\">Gricean maxims</a>) combined with the first two sub-maxims of Manner.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Horn1989_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Horn1989-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> The Q-principle states: \"Say as much as you can (given R).\"  As such it interacts with the <a href=\"/wiki/R-Principle\" title=\"R-Principle\">R-Principle</a>, which states: \"Say no more than you must (given Q).\" <sup id=\"cite_ref-SEP_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SEP-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> <sup id=\"cite_ref-ECS_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ECS-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> \n</p><p>The Q-Principle leads to the implication that if the speaker did not make a stronger statement (or say more), then its denial is (implied to be) true. For instance, the inference from \"He entered a house\" to \"He did not enter his own house\" is Q-based inference, i.e. deriving from the Q-Principle. <sup id=\"cite_ref-SEP_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SEP-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Q-principle&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-Horn1989-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Horn1989_1-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Horn, Laurence (1989). <i>A Natural History of Negation</i>. Chicago, IL: The University of Chicago press. pp.&#160;193\u2013203.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=A+Natural+History+of+Negation&amp;rft.place=Chicago%2C+IL&amp;rft.pages=193-203&amp;rft.pub=The+University+of+Chicago+press&amp;rft.date=1989&amp;rft.aulast=Horn&amp;rft.aufirst=Laurence&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AQ-principle\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-SEP-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-SEP_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-SEP_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"> <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/implicature/\">\"Implicature\"</a> in the <a href=\"/wiki/Stanford_Encyclopedia_of_Philosophy\" title=\"Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy\">Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy</a> .</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-ECS-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-ECS_3-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"> <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/0470018860.s00233/full\">\"The Gricean Model\"</a> in the Encyclopedia of Cognitive Science. </span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1266\nCached time: 20180909144254\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\